7","1205":"1205","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1136":"1136","1158":"1158","1168":"1168","1189":"1189","1200":"1200","1167":"1167","about 1205":"circa 1205","1166":"1166","about 1200":"circa 1200","Hatfield, Yorkshire, England":"Hatfield, Yorkshire, England","Eresby, Spilsby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Eresby, Spilsby, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England"},"en":{"1160–1217":"1160–1217","1158–1167":"1158–1167","1162–Female":"1162–Deceased","1164–Male":"1164–Deceased","1166–Female":"1166–Deceased","1168–Male":"1168–Deceased","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","1160–Female":"1160–Deceased","1189–1238":"1189–1238","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","1205–Male":"1205–Deceased","1136–1176":"1136–1176","1176":"1176","1164":"1164","1162":"1162","um 1190":"about 1190","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1217":"1217","1205":"1205","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1136":"1136","1158":"1158","1168":"1168","1189":"1189","1200":"1200","1167":"1167","about 1205":"about 1205","1166":"1166","about 1200":"about 1200","Hatfield, Yorkshire, England":"Hatfield, Yorkshire, England","Eresby, Spilsby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Eresby, Spilsby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"fitz","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a short form of any of the numerous names representing a transferred use of a surname formed with the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’, as for example   Fitzgerald  ,   Fitzroy  , or a transferred use of the surname <i>Fitz</i>, which may be of the same derivation, but applied originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same given name, or a local name from Fitz in Shropshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Fitt</i> + <i>hōh</i> ‘hill spur’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hatfield","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Hatfield (East Yorkshire, Yorkshire, Nottinghamshire, Worcestershire, Herefordshire, Hertfordshire, Essex), or Heathfield (Sussex, Somerset), though not all of these have given rise to hereditary surnames. The placenames derive from Old English <i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":55,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William fitz Simon of Hatfield was born in 1160, in Hatfield, Yorkshire, England as the son of Simon FitzAdam. He married Agnes de Kyme about 1190. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1217, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1160–1217":"1160–1217","1158–1167":"1158–1167","1162–Female":"1162–Surnud","1164–Male":"1164–Surnud","1166–Female":"1166–Surnud","1168–Male":"1168–Surnud","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1189–1238":"1189–1238","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1205–Male":"1205–Surnud","1136–1176":"1136–1176","1176":"1176","1164":"1164","1162":"1162","um 1190":"umbes 1190","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1217":"1217","1205":"1205","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1136":"1136","1158":"1158","1168":"1168","1189":"1189","1200":"1200","1167":"1167","about 1205":"umbes 1205","1166":"1166","about 1200":"umbes 1200","Hatfield, Yorkshire, England":"Hatfield, Yorkshire, England","Eresby, Spilsby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Eresby, Spilsby, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"1160–1217":"1160–1217","1158–1167":"1158–1167","1162–Female":"1162–Kuollut","1164–Male":"1164–Kuollut","1166–Female":"1166–Ku